     8	/**
     9	 * Represents a TEVM-enhanced viem client with an in-memory Ethereum client as its transport.
    10	 *
    11	 * The MemoryClient provides a complete in-memory Ethereum Virtual Machine implementation with
    12	 * a full suite of capabilities:
    13	 *
    14	 * - Execute contract calls directly in JavaScript with full EVM compatibility
    15	 * - Monitor EVM execution events (steps, messages, contract creation)
    16	 * - Deploy and interact with contracts, including direct Solidity imports
    17	 * - Set account states, balances, nonces, and contract storage
    18	 * - Fork from existing networks and cache remote state as needed
    19	 * - Mine blocks manually or automatically after transactions
    20	 * - Persist and restore state across sessions
    21	 *
    22	 * The client implements multiple API styles:
    23	 * - TEVM-specific methods for direct EVM interaction
    24	 * - Standard Ethereum JSON-RPC methods
    25	 * - Viem-compatible wallet, test, and public actions
    26	 *
    27	 * @type {import('./CreateMemoryClientFn.js').CreateMemoryClientFn}
    28	 *
    29	 * @example
    30	 * ```typescript
    31	 * import { createMemoryClient, http } from "tevm";
    32	 * import { optimism } from "tevm/common";
    33	 * import { parseEther } from "viem";
    34	 *
    35	 * // Create a client forking from Optimism
    36	 * const client = createMemoryClient({
    37	 *   fork: {
    38	 *     transport: http("https://mainnet.optimism.io")({}),
    39	 *   },
    40	 *   common: optimism,
    41	 * });
    42	 *
    43	 * // Wait for the client to be ready
    44	 * await client.tevmReady();
    45	 *
    46	 * // Set up account state
    47	 * const address = "0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890";
    48	 * await client.tevmSetAccount({
    49	 *   address,
    50	 *   balance: parseEther("10")
    51	 * });
    52	 *
    53	 * // Deploy a contract with events tracking
    54	 * const deployResult = await client.tevmDeploy({
    55	 *   bytecode: "0x608060405234801561001057600080fd5b50610150806100206000396000f3fe...",
    56	 *   abi: [...],
    57	 *   onStep: (step, next) => {
    58	 *     console.log(`Executing ${step.opcode.name} at PC=${step.pc}`);
    59	 *     next();
    60	 *   }
    61	 * });
    62	 *
    63	 * // Mine a block to confirm transactions
    64	 * await client.mine({ blocks: 1 });
    65	 *
    66	 * // Get the contract address from deployment
    67	 * console.log(`Contract deployed at: ${deployResult.createdAddress}`);
    68	 * ```
    69	 *
    70	 * @see For creating a MemoryClient instance, see {@link createMemoryClient}.
    71	 * @see [Client Guide](https://tevm.sh/learn/clients/)
    72	 * @see [Actions Guide](https://tevm.sh/learn/actions/)
    73	 * @see [Reference Docs](https://tevm.sh/reference/tevm/memory-client/functions/creatememoryclient/)
    74	 *
    75	 * ## Actions API
    76	 *
    77	 * MemoryClient supports the following viem actions:
    78	 *
    79	 * - [TEVM actions API](https://tevm.sh/reference/tevm/memory-client/type-aliases/tevmactions/)
    80	 * ```typescript
    81	 * import { createMemoryClient } from "tevm";
    82	 *
    83	 * const tevm = createMemoryClient();
    84	 * await tevm.setAccount({ address: `0x${'01'.repeat(20)}`, balance: 100n });
    85	 * ```
    86	 * - [Viem public actions API](https://viem.sh/docs/actions/public/introduction) such as [getBlockNumber](https://viem.sh/docs/actions/public/getBlockNumber)
    87	 * ```typescript
    88	 * import { createMemoryClient } from "tevm";
    89	 *
    90	 * const tevm = createMemoryClient();
    91	 * const bn = await tevm.getBlockNumber();
    92	 * ```
    93	 * - [Test actions](https://viem.sh/docs/actions/test/introduction) are included by default.
    94	 * ```typescript
    95	 * import { createMemoryClient } from "tevm";
    96	 *
    97	 * const tevm = createMemoryClient();
    98	 * await tevm.setBalance({ address: `0x${'01'.repeat(20)}`, balance: 100n });
    99	 * ```
   100	 *
   101	 * ## Forking
   102	 *
   103	 * To fork an existing network, pass an EIP-1193 transport to the `fork.transport` option with an optional block tag.
   104	 * When you fork, TEVM will pin the block tag and lazily cache state from the fork transport.
   105	 * It's highly recommended to pass in a `common` object that matches the chain. This will increase the performance of forking with known values.
   106	 *
   107	 * ```typescript
   108	 * import { createMemoryClient, http } from "tevm";
   109	 * import { optimism } from "tevm/common";
   110	 *
   111	 * const forkedClient = createMemoryClient({
   112	 *   fork: {
   113	 *     transport: http("https://mainnet.optimism.io")({}),
   114	 *     blockTag: '0xa6a63cd70fbbe396321ca6fe79e1b6735760c03538208b50d7e3a5dac5226435',
   115	 *   },
   116	 *   common: optimism,
   117	 * });
   118	 * ```
   119	 *
   120	 * The `common` object extends the viem chain interface with EVM-specific information. When using TEVM, you should also use `tevm/common` rather than `viem/chains` or use `createCommon` and pass in a viem chain.
   121	 *
   122	 * Viem clients, including MemoryClient, are themselves EIP-1193 transports. This means you can fork a client with another client.
   123	 *
   124	 * ## Mining Modes
   125	 *
   126	 * TEVM supports two mining modes:
   127	 * - Manual: Using `tevm.mine()`
   128	 * - Auto: Automatically mines a block after every transaction.
   129	 *
   130	 * TEVM state does not update until blocks are mined.
   131	 *
   132	 * ## Using TEVM over HTTP
   133	 *
   134	 * TEVM can be run as an HTTP server using `@tevm/server` to handle JSON-RPC requests.
   135	 *
   136	 * ```typescript
   137	 * import { createServer } from "tevm/server";
   138	 * import { createMemoryClient } from "tevm";
   139	 *
   140	 * const memoryClient = createMemoryClient();
   141	 *
   142	 * const server = createServer({
   143	 *   request: memoryClient.request,
   144	 * });
   145	 *
   146	 * server.listen(8545, () => console.log("listening on 8545"));
   147	 * ```
   148	 *
   149	 * This allows you to use any Ethereum client to communicate with it, including a viem public client.
   150	 *
   151	 * ```typescript
   152	 * import { createPublicClient, http } from "viem";
   153	 * import { mainnet } from "viem/chains";
   154	 *
   155	 * const publicClient = createPublicClient({
   156	 *   chain: mainnet,
   157	 *   transport: http("https://localhost:8545"),
   158	 * });
   159	 *
   160	 * console.log(await publicClient.getChainId());
   161	 * ```
   162	 *
   163	 * ## State Persistence (Experimental)
   164	 *
   165	 * It is possible to persist the TEVM client to a synchronous source using the `persister` option.
   166	 *
   167	 * ```typescript
   168	 * import { createMemoryClient, createSyncPersister } from "tevm";
   169	 * import { createMemoryClient } from "tevm/sync-storage-persister";
   170	 *
   171	 * // Client state will be hydrated and persisted from/to local storage
   172	 * const clientWithLocalStoragePersistence = createMemoryClient({
   173	 *   persister: createSyncPersister({
   174	 *     storage: localStorage,
   175	 *   }),
   176	 * });
   177	 * ```
   178	 *
   179	 * ## Network Support
   180	 *
   181	 * TEVM guarantees support for the following networks:
   182	 * - Ethereum mainnet
   183	 * - Standard OP Stack chains
   184	 *
   185	 * Other EVM chains are likely to work but do not officially carry support. More official chain support will be added in the near future.
   186	 *
   187	 * Note: Optimism deposit transactions are not currently supported but will be in a future release. TEVM filters out these transactions from blocks.
   188	 *
   189	 * ## Network and Hardfork Support
   190	 *
   191	 * TEVM supports enabling and disabling different EIPs, but the following EIPs are always turned on:
   192	 * - 1559
   193	 * - 4895
   194	 * - 4844
   195	 * - 4788
   196	 *
   197	 * Currently, only EIP-1559 Fee Market transactions are supported.
   198	 *
   199	 * ## Tree Shakeable Actions
   200	 *
   201	 * TEVM supports tree-shakeable actions using `createTevmNode()` and the `tevm/actions` package. If you are building a UI, you should use tree-shakeable actions to optimize bundle size. These are described in detail in the [actions API guide](https://tevm.sh/learn/actions/).
   202	 *
   203	 * ## Composing with TEVM Contracts and Bundler
   204	 *
   205	 * MemoryClient can compose with TEVM contracts and the TEVM bundler. For more information, see the [TEVM contracts guide](https://tevm.sh/learn/contracts/) and the [TEVM Solidity imports guide](https://tevm.sh/learn/solidity-imports/).
   206	 *
   207	 * ```typescript
   208	 * import { createMemoryClient } from "tevm";
   209	 * import { MyERC721 } from './MyERC721.sol';
   210	 *
   211	 * const tevm = createMemoryClient({
   212	 *   fork: {
   213	 *     transport: http("https://mainnet.optimism.io")({}),
   214	 *   },
   215	 * });
   216	 *
   217	 * const address = '0xd8dA6BF26964aF9D7eEd9e03E53415D37aA96045';
   218	 *
   219	 * await tevm.runContractCall(
   220	 *   MyERC721.write.mint({
